etable Models:** Create interpretable models that provide insights into how personalization affects model performance.\n4. **Robustness to Data Drift:** Develop methods that ensure models remain robust to changes in data distribution over time.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe key challenge in Federated Learning is statistical heterogeneity, which makes it difficult to create a global model that generalizes well to each client. While existing methods have addressed this issue to some extent, there is a need for more dynamic, scalable, interpretable, and robust solutions.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nFederated Learning (FL) is a promising approach for training models on decentralized data while preserving privacy. However, statistical heterogeneity across clients poses significant challenges, particularly in creating a global model that generalizes well to each client.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we dynamically adjust the degree of personalization in Federated Learning to better handle statistical heterogeneity across clients?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nAddressing this problem is crucial for improving the performance and applicability of Federated Learning in real-world scenarios. Dynamic personalization can lead to more accurate and robust models, enhancing the utility of FL in various domains. This research will advance the state of the art in FL and contribute to the development of more effective and scalable solutions.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nDynamic personalization requires sophisticated algorithms that can adapt to varying levels of heterogeneity across clients. This involves complex decision-making processes and may require significant computational resources. Additionally, ensuring that the personalization process is both efficient and effective is challenging.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious methods have focused on static personalization or have not fully addressed the dynamic nature of client data. The complexity of adapting to varying levels of heterogeneity and the need for efficient algorithms have been significant barriers. Additionally, there is a lack of comprehensive frameworks that integrate dynamic personalization with other aspects of FL.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed approach involves developing a dynamic personalization framework that adjusts the degree of personalization based on the heterogeneity of client data. This will include:\n- **Algorithm Design:** Designing algorithms that can dynamically adjust personalization.\n- **Evaluation Metrics:** Developing metrics to evaluate the performance and robustness of the proposed framework.\n- **Experiments:** Conducting experiments on real-world datasets to demonstrate the effectiveness of the approach.\n\nExpected outcomes include a more accurate, robust, and scalable Federated Learning framework that can handle statistical heterogeneity across clients. This will advance the state of the art in FL and contribute to its broader adoption in real-world applications."}

