ove model performance and generalization?",\n\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Dynamic learning rate adjustment can significantly enhance the performance and generalization of personalized models in Federated Learning (FL), making it more effective for real-world applications. This research will advance the state-of-the-art in pFL by addressing the challenges of statistical heterogeneity. Solving this problem will lead to more robust and adaptable models, benefiting various domains such as healthcare, finance, and IoT, where data is inherently distributed and heterogeneous.",\n\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "Dynamic learning rate adjustment in pFL is challenging due to the need to balance local and global model updates while considering the diverse characteristics of client data. Naive approaches may fail because they do not account for the unique statistical properties of each client\'s data, leading to suboptimal model performance. Technical obstacles include the computational complexity of real-time learning rate adjustments and the need for efficient communication between clients and the server. Theoretical challenges involve developing algorithms that can adapt learning rates in a way that maintains convergence and generalization across different clients.",\n\n  "[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?": "Previous research in pFL has focused on other aspects such as model aggregation and client selection, but dynamic learning rate adjustment has not been extensively explored. Existing solutions often use static learning rates or simple heuristics, which may not be sufficient for handling the complexities of statistical heterogeneity. The gap lies in the lack of a comprehensive framework that can dynamically adjust learning rates based on client-specific data characteristics and model performance metrics. Our approach aims to fill this gap by developing a novel algorithm that addresses these challenges.",\n\n  "[Questio