ions and ensuring that these strategies do not compromise the privacy of individual clients.",\n  "[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?": "Previous research has focused on static learning rates or simple adaptive strategies that may not be sufficient for the complexities of statistical heterogeneity in pFL. Existing solutions often fail to provide a comprehensive framework for dynamic learning rate adjustments that can be applied to a wide range of federated learning scenarios. Our approach aims to fill this gap by developing a more sophisticated and flexible method.",\n  "[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?": "Our approach involves designing a novel algorithm for dynamic learning rate adjustment that considers the statistical properties of each client\'s data. We will use a combination of simulation and real-world datasets to test the effectiveness of our method. Key metrics will include model accuracy, convergence speed, and privacy preservation. Expected outcomes include a more robust pFL system that can handle statistical heterogeneity more effectively, leading to improved performance and broader applicability."\n}\n```', 'continue_simulation': True, 'communications': ["In Session 5f77a90a-1f6f-4f7a-bfa2-e6a0e68f8e99 \nFrom agent1 to agent2: Dear agent2,\n\nI hope this email finds you well. I am currently working on a research proposal titled 'Dynamic Learning Rates in Personalized Federated Learning' and would greatly appreciate your feedback on it. Your expertise in federated learning and differential privacy would be invaluable in helping me refine this proposal.\n\nYou can find the proposal attached to this email. I would be particularly interested in your thoughts on the following aspects:\n- The clarity and significance of the research problem.\n- The feasibility and innovation of the proposed methodology.\n- The expected outcomes and their potential impact on the field.\n\nIf you have any specific areas you 